      <!-- Introduction -->
      <section class="section" data-section="intro" id="intro">
        <div class="section-content">
          <span class="section-number">01 — Introduction</span>
          <h2 class="section-title">What Are Boids?</h2>
          <div class="section-text">
            <p>
              In 1986, computer scientist <strong>Craig Reynolds</strong> developed
              a groundbreaking artificial life simulation that would change how we
              understand emergent behavior in complex systems.
            </p>
            <p>
              The word "boid" is simply a corruption of "bird" — these are
              simulated bird-like agents that follow incredibly simple rules,
              yet produce stunningly realistic flocking behavior without any
              centralized control.
            </p>
          </div>
          <blockquote class="quote-block">
            "Flocks, herds, and schools are examples of aggregate motion. Groups
            of creatures moving together form elegant and complex patterns."
            <div class="quote-author">— Craig Reynolds, 1987</div>
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- The Three Rules -->
      <section class="section" data-section="rules">
        <div class="section-content">
          <span class="section-number">02 — The Algorithm</span>
          <h2 class="section-title">Three Simple Rules</h2>
          <div class="section-text">
            <p>
              The magic of Boids lies in their simplicity. Each agent follows
              only three behavioral rules, applied locally — there is no global
              coordination, no leader, no predetermined patterns.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="rules-grid">
            <div class="rule-card">
              <div class="rule-number">1</div>
              <h3 class="rule-title">Separation</h3>
              <p class="rule-desc">
                Steer to avoid crowding local flockmates. Each boid maintains
                personal space, preventing collisions.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="rule-card">
              <div class="rule-number">2</div>
              <h3 class="rule-title">Alignment</h3>
              <p class="rule-desc">
                Steer towards the average heading of local flockmates. Boids
                tend to fly in the same direction as their neighbors.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="rule-card">
              <div class="rule-number">3</div>
              <h3 class="rule-title">Cohesion</h3>
              <p class="rule-desc">
                Steer to move toward the average position of local flockmates.
                This keeps the flock together as a group.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

